## Key Finding

A Random Forest model trained on socio-economic features explains **{{ (r2 * 100)|round(1) }}%** of variation in bus coverage across England's LSOAs (R² = {{ r2|round(3) }}). This means {% if r2 > 0.4 %}a substantial majority of the geographic variation in bus service levels can be predicted from demographics and deprivation indicators alone — confirming that service distribution is not random but structurally driven by measurable factors.{% else %}a meaningful but minority share of service variation is demographically explained — other factors including historical investment decisions, operator commercial judgements, and planning constraints account for the remainder.{% endif %}

## Feature Importance (SHAP)

{%- if top_feature is defined and top_feature -%}
The strongest predictor is **{{ top_feature }}** (SHAP importance: {{ top_importance|round(3) }}). {% if top_feature == "nocar_pct" %}Car ownership rate is the dominant predictor of bus coverage — areas with high car-free households receive more bus service. This reflects commercial logic: operators route services where captive passengers exist. However, it also reveals a circularity: low car ownership attracts service, but service absence forces car ownership. Communities newly falling into transport poverty may lose services precisely when they most need them.{% elif top_feature == "imd_score" %}IMD deprivation score is the top predictor — a concerning finding if it indicates services cluster in less deprived areas, or a positive finding if deprived areas are better served due to targeted subsidy.{% elif top_feature == "population_density" %}Population density is the primary driver, consistent with commercial route economics favouring high-demand corridors.{% else %}{{ top_feature }} emerges as the primary driver of service distribution, warranting further investigation into the mechanism driving this association.{% endif %}
