## Model Limitations

The Random Forest model captures correlations, not causation. High R² means demographics are good predictors of service, not that demographics cause service levels. The model cannot distinguish between communities that have poor service because of their demographics and communities whose demographics have been shaped by decades of poor service (reverse causation). Policy evaluation should use this model as a diagnostic tool, not as a causal framework.

## Policy Implications

The {{ (r2 * 100)|round(1) }}% explanatory power{% if top_feature is defined and top_feature %} — with {{ top_feature }} as the dominant feature{% endif %} — provides LTAs with a data-driven targeting tool. LSOAs where predicted coverage (from demographics) significantly exceeds actual coverage are the clearest candidates for intervention: the model says they "should" have more service based on who lives there, but they don't. These over-under areas represent the most tractable policy targets under BSIP frameworks.

